<statement>
<p>
Define a relation on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> as <m>x \rel y</m> if <m>|x-y|  \lt  1</m>. Is <m>R</m> reflexive? Symmetric? Transitive?
</p>
</statement>
<solution>

<proof><p>
We show that the relation is reflexive and symmetric but not transitive.
<ul>
<li>
<p>
 Reflexive. For all <m>x\in\mathbb{R}</m> we have <m>|x-x|=0 \lt 1</m>. Thus, <m>x\rel x</m> for any <m>x\in\mathbb{R}</m>.
  </p></li>
<li>
<p>
 Symmetric. Since <m>|x-y|=|y-x|</m>, we see that if <m>x\rel y</m>, that is, <m>|x-y| \lt 1</m>, then <m>|y-x| \lt 1</m>, which implies <m>y\rel x</m>.
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
 Not transitive. Consider <m>x=0</m>, <m>y=3/4</m>, and <m>z=3/2</m>. Then we see that <m>|x-y| \lt 1</m> and <m>|y-z| \lt 1</m>, but <m>|x-z|=3/2 \gt 1</m>. Thus, <m>x\rel y</m>, <m>y\rel z</m>, but <m>x</m> is not related to <m>z</m>. Therefore the relation is not transitive.
</p></li>
</ul>
</p></proof>

</solution>
</exercise>